phases.content:
**Discovery:** No Rust change needed. The existing `GitHubIssue` struct (`github.rs:32-42`) already includes `labels: Vec<GitHubLabel>` with name, color, description. The `gh issue view --json labels` invocation already requests them. The frontend just doesn't *type* them in.

**Three changes, all TypeScript + CSS:**

**1. `useDependencyGraph.ts` — surface labels through FetchedIssue → IssueNodeData**

Extend `FetchedIssue`:
```ts
interface FetchedIssue {
  number: number;
  title: string;
  body?: string;
  state: string;
  phaseCount?: number;
  labels?: { name: string; color: string }[];
}
```

In the fallback object inside the `.catch()` of `fetch_github_issue_by_number`, add `labels: []` (since errors won't have labels):
```ts
.catch(() => ({
  number: issue.number,
  title: issue.title,
  body: undefined,
  state: 'open',
  labels: [],
}))
```

Thread labels into `IssueNodeData` in the nodes.map block:
```ts
data: {
  issueNumber: issue.number,
  title: issue.title,
  status: resolveStatus(issue),
  phaseProgress: resolvePhaseProgress(issue),
  phaseCount: issue.phaseCount,
  labels: issue.labels ?? [],
}
```

**2. `IssueNode.tsx` — render the chip row**

Extend `IssueNodeData`:
```ts
export type IssueNodeData = {
  // ...
  labels?: { name: string; color: string }[];
};
```

After `.issue-node-title` and before the progress bar, render chips:
```tsx
{data.labels && data.labels.length > 0 && (
  <div className="issue-node-labels" aria-hidden="true">
    {data.labels.slice(0, 4).map((l) => (
      <span
        key={l.name}
        className="issue-node-label-chip"
        style={{ backgroundColor: `#${l.color}` }}
        title={l.name}
      />
    ))}
    {data.labels.length > 4 && (
      <span className="issue-node-label-overflow" title={data.labels.slice(4).map((l) => l.name).join(', ')}>
        +{data.labels.length - 4}
      </span>
    )}
  </div>
)}
```

The `data.labels.slice(4).map(...).join(', ')` on the overflow title surfaces the hidden label names on hover, so they aren't completely lost.

**3. `IssueNode.css` — chip styling**

Add:
```css
.issue-node-labels {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  gap: 3px;
  margin-top: 2px;
  margin-bottom: 4px;
}

.issue-node-label-chip {
  display: inline-block;
  width: 10px;
  height: 6px;
  border-radius: 2px;
  flex-shrink: 0;
}

.issue-node-label-overflow {
  font-size: 9px;
  color: var(--text-secondary, #888);
  margin-left: 2px;
  letter-spacing: 0.2px;
}
```

Chip dimensions match the issue's spec (6×10px pill, 3px gap). Color comes from inline style (GitHub hex sans `#`).

**Why no min-width changes to the node:** The current `min-width: 160px; max-width: 220px` (IssueNode.css:7-8) accommodates up to ~4 chips + overflow indicator at ~62px row width comfortably. No layout reflow needed.

**Why slice(0, 4) is a hard cap:** Past 4 chips the row gets unreadable as encoding, and most issues won't have more than 4 labels anyway. The +N indicator is the escape hatch for the edge case.
